"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889993","Home Office","false","2018-04-26","<p>This question cannot be answered because any cases referred by Immigration Compliance &amp; Enforcement teams to investigate the perpetrators of trafficking and modern slavery which are subsequently adopted by Immigration Enforcement crime teams, police or GLAA to investigate, will be commissioned under new operation names and taken forward on a case by case basis by the agency most suited to the specific circumstances encountered.</p><p>This process involves multiple case management systems and does not afford the capability to link subsequent investigations back to the operation from where the referral was originally made.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-26T12:23:27.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889993/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889993/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-23","Construction: Undocumented Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2018 to Question 135421, how many arrests of potential perpetrators of trafficking and modern slavery were made in relation to cases of trafficking identified during Operation Magnify; and what the outcome of those arrests has been.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","137045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889994","Home Office","false","2018-04-30","<p>Project AIDANT is the series of multi-agency operational intensifications to tackle modern slavery and human trafficking led by the National Crime Agency. During 2017 all UK territorial police forces, including the British Transport Police, took part along with other law enforcement agencies including the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority, Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, Europol, DWP, HMRC and Regional Organised Crime Units. Activities under Project AIDANT were also supported by NGOs, Local Authorities and Fire and Rescue Services in some areas.</p><p> </p><p>During 2017, over 560 potential victims were identified through Project AIDANT activity with 57 cases reported as having been referred to the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) and 77 to Duty to Notify (DtN). The number of potential victims includes victims encountered overseas during the operations who do not qualify for referral to the UK NRM and DTN.</p><p>Data on arrests for illegal working is not captured by the NCA.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","137047 ; 137048","2018-04-30T15:29:59.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889994/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889994/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-23","Human Trafficking: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which agency is leading Operation Aidant; and between which agencies have partnership agreements been established.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","137046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889995","Home Office","false","2018-04-30","<p>Project AIDANT is the series of multi-agency operational intensifications to tackle modern slavery and human trafficking led by the National Crime Agency. During 2017 all UK territorial police forces, including the British Transport Police, took part along with other law enforcement agencies including the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority, Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, Europol, DWP, HMRC and Regional Organised Crime Units. Activities under Project AIDANT were also supported by NGOs, Local Authorities and Fire and Rescue Services in some areas.</p><p> </p><p>During 2017, over 560 potential victims were identified through Project AIDANT activity with 57 cases reported as having been referred to the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) and 77 to Duty to Notify (DtN). The number of potential victims includes victims encountered overseas during the operations who do not qualify for referral to the UK NRM and DTN.</p><p>Data on arrests for illegal working is not captured by the NCA.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","137046 ; 137048","2018-04-30T15:29:59.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889995/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889995/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-23","Human Trafficking: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many potential victims of trafficking have been (a) identified and (b) referred to the National Referral Mechanism under Operation Aidant.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","137047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889996","Home Office","false","2018-04-30","<p>Project AIDANT is the series of multi-agency operational intensifications to tackle modern slavery and human trafficking led by the National Crime Agency. During 2017 all UK territorial police forces, including the British Transport Police, took part along with other law enforcement agencies including the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority, Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, Europol, DWP, HMRC and Regional Organised Crime Units. Activities under Project AIDANT were also supported by NGOs, Local Authorities and Fire and Rescue Services in some areas.</p><p> </p><p>During 2017, over 560 potential victims were identified through Project AIDANT activity with 57 cases reported as having been referred to the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) and 77 to Duty to Notify (DtN). The number of potential victims includes victims encountered overseas during the operations who do not qualify for referral to the UK NRM and DTN.</p><p>Data on arrests for illegal working is not captured by the NCA.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","137046 ; 137047","2018-04-30T15:29:59.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889996/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889996/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-23","Human Trafficking: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many arrests for illegal working have been made during Operation Aidant.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","137048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889997","Home Office","false","2018-04-26","<p>Since the commencement of the scheme in February 2008 to 31 March 2018; 20,315 initial decision illegal working civil penalties have been issued .</p><p>Please note the figures are for penalties levied at the initial decision stage which may be reduced, cancelled, increased or reissued at the objection or appeal stage.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-26T12:32:50.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889997/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889997/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-23","Undocumented Workers: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2018 to Question 135084, how many fines for the employment of illegal workers have been levied since the commencement of the scheme in 2008.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","137049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889998","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-30","<p>The Department has commissioned through its Social Care Policy Research Programme a review of the effectiveness of interventions for children and young people (aged 3-18 years) who have experienced adverse childhood experiences (ACEs). This will report later this year.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is aware of the range of published evidence on the importance of ACEs and the potential impact they have on health, including mental health.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-04-30T09:46:26.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889998/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/889998/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-23","Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has made an recent assessment of the link between adverse childhood experiences and (a) risky health behaviours, (b) chronic health conditions and (c) premature death.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","137050"
